{{About|films in the year 1921|the Indian film about the Mappila Uprising|1921 (1988 film)|the Indian horror film|1921 (2018 film)}} {{refimprove|date=July 2017}} {{Year nav topic5|1921|film}} {{Yearsinfilm}}
The following is an overview of '''1921 in film''', including significant events, a list of films released and notable births and deaths.
==Events== *January 21 – The [[Silent film|silent]] [[comedy-drama]] ''[[The Kid (1921 film)|The Kid]]'', written by, produced by, directed by and starring [[Charlie Chaplin]] (in his Tramp character) &ndash; his first full-length film as a director &ndash; and featuring [[Jackie Coogan]], is released in the United States. It is the year's second-highest-grossing film. *March 6 – The silent [[Epic film|epic]] [[war film]] ''[[The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (film)|The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse]]'', adapted for the screen by [[June Mathis]], is released in the United States. It is the year's highest-grossing film (and the sixth-best-grossing silent film of all time), propels [[Rudolph Valentino]] to stardom and inspires a [[tango]] craze and a fashion for [[gaucho]] pants. *September 5 – Popular comedian [[Roscoe "Fatty" Arbuckle]] attends a party at the [[St. Francis Hotel]], San Francisco, during which actress [[Virginia Rappe]] is fatally injured; although he is eventually acquitted of rape and manslaughter, the scandal derails his career. *October 21 – [[George Melford]]'s silent film ''[[The Sheik (film)|The Sheik]]'', which enhances leading actor [[Rudolph Valentino]]'s international reputation as a [[Latin lover (stereotype)|Latin lover]], is premiered in Los Angeles. Within the first year of its release, it exceeds $1 million in ticket sales. *October 26 – The [[Chicago Theatre]], which will be the oldest surviving French-style [[Baroque Revival architecture|Baroque Revival]] grand movie palace, opens. *The [[Experimental film|experimental]] short [[documentary film]] ''[[Manhatta]]'' is shot by painter [[Charles Sheeler]] and photographer [[Paul Strand]] in New York City.
